gtts-cli "Artemisia can be grown in pots or open ground. Remove stones and weeds, create a barrier so cattle and animals do not enter, and plow only if you need to. If it is the rainy season, dig drainage channels to drain the soil. Any kind of straw, grass, leftovers from cereal crops, cut or crushed corn plants, and decomposed palm oil leaves can be used as organic fertilizer or mulch. Avoid woody material because it attracts termites." -l en -o en/audio/en-cultivation.mp3
gtts-cli "Artemisia plants need at least 1 meter between them because they grow 1 meter wide. For example, plant them 1 meter apart in a row, with a 2 meter gap for the next row.  Alternating artemisia with trees and other crops is good for keeping soil nutrition balanced. Artemisia is fragile in the first few months. Water it in the morning and evening every day for the first three months. Use the morning and evening to avoid plant water loss from the daytime heat. After three months, it can be watered 2 or 3 times a week." -l en -o en/audio/en-planting.mp3
gtts-cli "Do not harvest in the rainy season because the moisture creates bacteria and mold. Harvest in the driest season, in the middle of the day, if possible, and dry the harvested plant immediately. Leave the finest and best plants to flower to collect their seeds. Harvested plants can be used to make medicines, tea, soaps, and more." -l en -o en/audio/en-harvesting.mp3
